":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"f19086c78390","_type":"image","alt":"soft bar material","asset":{"_id":"image-9b012356df9e1359a05fac1b27501340dd583178-1080x1350-png","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":0.8,"height":1350,"width":1080},"lqip":"data:image/png;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},{"_key":"71c707b0f1ef","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"83eebc0007020","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Carl explains “I was looking for something that feels and looks like the other cool and elevated spots, but most of those places are very limited in their non-alc options. I don't drink alcohol and I don't drink coffee, so I don't exist in New York City.\""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"fdbb6489531c","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"6b137170b7010","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Typical NA spaces are sterile, either with no space to enjoy beverages or limited hours. With 38% of Americans who choose not to drink alcohol and many consciously shifting away from sugary mocktails, Soft Bar aims to be a space for everyone to exist. The menu will feature soft cocktails and functional drinks that naturally enhance well-being, perfect for anyone looking to sip and socialize or enjoy a drink with added benefits."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"79294485ca8a","_type":"image","alt":"soft bar","asset":{"_id":"image-b31ce3a05b109e79cad2b83b6b80f63a50a32cf9-1080x1437-jpg","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":0.7515657620041754,"height":1437,"width":1080},"lqip":"data:image/jpeg;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},{"_key":"6f45b351eed4","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"6d05bdbb2f0a0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Radke’s vision includes a morning café featuring local coffee roasters, a daytime workspace/creative studio, an evening bar and an event space with fitness leaders, gatherings, and music—amplified with community and meaningful connections. Bolt’s focus is to create an all encompassing third-space that can evolve to embrace all these facets."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"94c39ecb5076","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"a7500110dce9","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"5f647afe7e9b","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"762ea4726c66","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"788d296d3b56","_type":"image","alt":"soft bar","asset":{"_id":"image-bcddbc60824c4c3b3959e4bccf250802a8967153-1080x1440-jpg","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":0.75,"height":1440,"width":1080},"lqip":"data:image/jpeg;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},{"_key":"28b098c95589","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"7a88ccfe10cf0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The 2,300 SF space in Greenpoint is a former industrial garage with exposed brick and concrete floors, which will be enhanced by an infinite bar and a glass facade. The space is designed to emphasize natural materials, calming lighting, and a cozy, mindful atmosphere. The color palette features soothing naturals, warm neutrals, and muted dark pastels. Soft wood fixtures and plush furniture offset the industrial shell, while luxurious stone accents and clean lines bring the space together."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"}],"featuredImage":{"_key":null,"_type":"image","asset":{"_id":"image-f4041dab58c157cbbcfe81f7979daa55a59e4d3d-1920x1080-png","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":1.7777777777777777,"height":1080,"width":1920},"lqip":"data:image/png;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},"publishedAt":"2025-09-02","slug":"clientspotlight-softbar","summary":"Bolt Builds partnered with Carl Radke to bring Soft Bar to life, a non-alcoholic bar and café in Greenpoint designed as an inclusive, flexible third-space for connection, creativity, and mindful consumption.","title":"Client Spotlight | Soft Bar "},"nextInsight":{"_id":"863b1d55-8b8b-421e-812b-89f2a97218a0","_type":"insight","content":[{"_key":"84769fd5b498","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"7e3ef67a15d9","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Breeze Blocks"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h2"},{"_key":"4dd6723e55bd","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"005785c7918f","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"\nFrom raw origins to refined forms, we spotlight the materials that shape how we build, live, and experience spaces."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"3e160f1a4456","_type":"image","alt":"breeze blocks bolt builds ","asset":{"_id":"image-2fe2736c44ecda8cdfe78798f77c408ee835c414-1920x1080-png","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":1.7777777777777777,"height":1080,"width":1920},"lqip":"data:image/png;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},{"_key":"7113f986627b","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"40b72b0992990","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"These patterned decorative blocks made of concrete or clay became popular in the 1950s and ’60s Mid-Century Modern era. Used on walls and facades, they provide shade, airflow, privacy, and protection. All while adding stylish geometric patterns, especially suited to warmer climates."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"ed0aec1138e2","_type":"image","alt":"breeze blocks tamara wibowo architects ","asset":{"_id":"image-32ab7746ef01cf8cb0fe82905378ddbf52e9528b-1000x563-jpg","_type":"sanity.imageAsset","description":null,"metadata":{"dimensions":{"aspectRatio":1.7761989342806395,"height":563,"width":1000},"lqip":"data:image/jpeg;base64,"},"tags":null},"caption":null,"crop":null},{"_key":"aa6fcfca6596","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"787a10779406","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Breeze Blocks House by Tamara Wibowo Architects uses breeze blocks as a defining feature, shaping both the exterior and interior of the home. These patterne